const prev = null;
const next = null;
---

<Article
  title="Signed Distance Functions"
  description="Primitives, boolean operations, smooth blending, and domain transformations."
  prev={prev}
  next={next}
  chapterIndex={2}
>

  <h1>Signed Distance Functions</h1>
  <p class="lead">
    A signed distance function returns the shortest distance from any point in
    space to the nearest surface — negative inside, positive outside, zero on
    the surface. This simple contract unlocks a rich algebra of shape operations.
  </p>

  <h2>Primitives</h2>

  <p>
    Every SDF scene is built from primitives. Here are the three most useful ones:
  </p>

  <pre><code>// Sphere centered at origin, radius r
float sdSphere(vec3 p, float r) &#123;
  return length(p) - r;
&#125;

// Axis-aligned box, half-extents b
float sdBox(vec3 p, vec3 b) &#123;
  vec3 q = abs(p) - b;
  return length(max(q, 0.0)) + min(max(q.x, max(q.y, q.z)), 0.0);
&#125;

// Capsule from a to b, radius r
float sdCapsule(vec3 p, vec3 a, vec3 b, float r) &#123;
  vec3 ab = b - a, ap = p - a;
  float t = clamp(dot(ap, ab) / dot(ab, ab), 0.0, 1.0);
  return length(ap - ab * t) - r;
&#125;</code></pre>

  <p>
    To place a primitive somewhere in the world, subtract its position from
    <code>p</code> before passing it in: <code>sdSphere(p - center, r)</code>.
    This is a <em>domain translation</em>.
  </p>

  <h2>Boolean operations</h2>

  <p>
    Because SDFs are just numbers, combining shapes is arithmetic:
  </p>

  <pre><code>float opUnion    (float a, float b) &#123; return min(a, b);  &#125;  // A or B
float opSubtract (float a, float b) &#123; return max(-a, b); &#125;  // B minus A
float opIntersect(float a, float b) &#123; return max(a, b);  &#125;  // A and B</code></pre>

  <p>
    These are exact for convex primitives, and approximate (but visually
    correct) for anything more complex.
  </p>

  <h2>Smooth union</h2>

  <p>
    Hard boolean operations produce sharp creases. A smooth union blends the
    boundary between two surfaces, producing an organic merge. The blend radius
    is controlled by <code>k</code>:
  </p>

  <pre><code>float opSmoothUnion(float a, float b, float k) &#123;
  float h = clamp(0.5 + 0.5 * (b - a) / k, 0.0, 1.0);
  return mix(b, a, h) - k * h * (1.0 - h);
&#125;</code></pre>

  <p>
    The demo below uses smooth union to blend two spheres and a box. The blend
    radius is animated — watch how the surfaces melt into one another.
  </p>

  <ShaderCanvas
    src={sdfSrc}
    height={400}
    caption="Smooth union of two spheres and a box — all from three SDF primitives."
  />

  <h2>Domain transformations</h2>

  <p>
    Because we evaluate the SDF by transforming <code>p</code> before calling a
    primitive, we can apply any spatial operation for free:
  </p>

  <pre><code>// Rotation — rotate p before evaluating
vec3 rotateY(vec3 p, float a) &#123;
  float s = sin(a), c = cos(a);
  return vec3(c*p.x + s*p.z, p.y, -s*p.x + c*p.z);
&#125;

// Uniform scale — scale p, then compensate the result
float sdScaled(vec3 p, float s) &#123;
  return sdSphere(p / s, 1.0) * s;
&#125;

// Infinite repetition — wrap space into a tile
float opRep(vec3 p, vec3 cell) &#123;
  vec3 q = mod(p + 0.5 * cell, cell) - 0.5 * cell;
  return sdSphere(q, 0.4);
&#125;</code></pre>

  <div class="note">
    <strong>Note:</strong> domain repetition (<code>opRep</code>) is covered in
    depth in <a href="/05-domain-repetition">Chapter 5</a>.
  </div>

</Article>
